Detect dense LD block structure:

The dense LD block structure detection can be performed either in MATLAB or called by R.

Before conducting the dense LD block structure detecton, make sure the elements on the diagonal of the matrix are zero. If not, covert them to zero and save in another CSV file.

# Uncomment to convert the elements on the diagonal of the matrix to zero: 
# diag(geno)<-0

# Please see "demo_mat.html" for an example of dense LD block structure detection using MATLAB.
# Import results obtained by MATLAB:
DenseLDmx_matlab=readMat("DenseLDmx.mat")


# The MATLAB function "denseLD.m" for dense LD block structure detection can also be called by R as follows:

## Tell MATLAB the locations of input and output data you would like to keep.
file_location <-"data_directory"
filename="demo_ldmx.csv"
mat_function_dir<-"addpath('MATLAB_function_directory');"

## Set parameters 
# LDcut=0.7 # Threshold (LD score)
# iter=10 # Iteration for learning the structure
# k1=1 
# kn=460 # The number has to be smaller than the total number of SNPs. If error occurs, change to a smaller number.
# leap=10 
# fig=0 # Can be 0 or 1.

## Conduct the detection
# Default parameter values: LDcut=0.5, iter=10, k1=1, leap=10, fig=0
# Have to specify kn. This number has to be smaller than the total number of SNPs. If error occurs, change to a smaller number.
DenseLDmx_R<-denseLD_block(input_location=file_location, filename=filename, mat_function_dir=mat_function_dir, output = "DenseLDmx",
                     cnames = 1,rnames = 0, kn=460)
## Rearrange the SNPs according to the dense LD structure using function denseLD_order. You can also arrange the SNPs using your own code.
DenseLDmx <- DenseLDmx_R
ldmx.dense=denseLD_order(DenseLDmx) # Use output either from MATLAB or R.
colnames(ldmx.dense)[2]<-"DENSEorder"
# ldmx.dense$rsID=colnames(ldmx)
lm.results.1=merge(lm.results,ldmx.dense,by="BPorder")

Generate adjacency matrix and the corresponding graph object according to dense LD block structure

cindx=data.frame(t(DenseLDmx$Cindx))
colnames(cindx)[1]="block.ID"
cindx$rsID=colnames(geno)
clist=data.frame(t(DenseLDmx$Clist))
colnames(clist)[1]="DENSEorder"
clist$rsID=colnames(geno)
clist$BPorder=rownames(clist)
cid=data.frame(t(DenseLDmx$CID))
colnames(cid)[1]="block.ID"
cid$block.rank=rownames(cid)

## select blocks with more than one SNPs, excluding block.ID = -1:
block<-data.frame(table(cindx$block.ID)) #[-1,]
colnames(block)[1]=c("block.ID")
block1=merge(cid,block,by=c("block.ID"))
block1[,c(1:ncol(block1))]<-sapply(block1[,c(1:ncol(block1))],as.numeric)
block1<-block1[order(block1$block.rank),]
block1$pairs <- block1$Freq*(block1$Freq-1)/2
sum(block1$pairs)

block1$D<-ifelse(block1$Freq>1, 1,0) # blocks with more than 1 SNP is denoted as 1, otherwise denoted as 0.

Trend plot of beta by lambda (remove extreme beta):

In previous plot, one SNP has extreme beta values; hence, the trend of other SNPs cannot be properly observed. Here, we zoom in the trend for other SNPs by removing the SNP with extreme values.
